to get to root
22/tcp SSH Brute-force credentials, exploit version-specific vulnerabilities. Example
user enumeration, denial of service. Or use stolen keys for remote access.
80/tcp HTTP Web application attacks, or access sensitive files.
139/tcp NetBios Enumerate shares, users, and workgroups
445/tcp SMB Access file shares, exploit SMBv1 vulnerabilities, or perform pass-the-hash
attacks.
2. What vulnerabilities are likely present based on the version?
• vsftpd 2.3.4 – Backdoor sending a username triggers a
backdoor on port 6200, giving a root shell.
• OpenSSH 5.3p1 – Weak ciphers off-by-one error in sshd,
user enumeration. No trivial remote RCE,
butpost-authentication risks.
• Apache 2.2.8 – Multiple vulnerabilities: Range header DoS,
HTTP request smuggling, and if PHP/mod_cgi is present, RCE
is possible.
• Windows 7 SP1 (SMB) – Highly vulnerable to EternalBlue
(MS17-010) – unauthenticated remote code execution on
SMBv1. Also SMBv1 DoS, information disclosure, and
potential for wormable attacks.
3. Which one is the highest risk and why?
• Port 445 (SMB) on Windows 7 SP1: Microsoft no longer
releases new security patches unless under a paid ESU plan.
Meaning it extremely exploitable.
4. What attack path can be built from this?
• Reconnaissance – Use nmap scripts to confirm EternalBlue
vulnerability.
• Initial compromise – Exploit EternalBlue via Metasploit
• Post-exploitation – Dump hashes, install backdoors, enable
RDP, or pivot to internal networks.
5. What should be the remediation?
• Vsftpd: Upgrade to the latest version.
• SSH: Update to OpenSSH latest version. Disable weak algorithms, use key-based
auth.
• Apache: Update to OpenSSH 8.x (latest). Disable weak algorithms, use key-based
auth, implement fail2ban.
• General: Run regular vulnerability scans, enforce least privilege, and maintain a
patch management policy.
